comment_text_display: The Bravia 9 would be better than the QM7, it’s more on par with the QM8.  I sit about the same distance as you and have the 83 inch G4. The Bravia 9 is very nice and I almost switched to that but the micro contrast from OLED is just something you can’t live without it once you have it.  I think at 6 feet I wouldn’t go more than 83–85 inch, if you’re at eight or nine, I could see going to 98 but  any closer and that’s going to start to feel overwhelming, especially closeups in movies, and could give you a little bit of motion sickness.  The C5 and 83 inches is probably the best value for an OLED in that size, the G5 is better but significantly more expensive. Unless you could get a closeout 83 inch G4, that would also be a great choice. The HDR brightness is very impressive on the newer OLEDs.

comment_text_display:
I have both the 75" and the 65" in this QNED86 range.... Previously came from an LG OLED 65" which developed burn in.
I have working in the Pro AV Events industry for over 20 years and stare at displays for a living (specifically Projectors, Large format LED walls and displays like these) and theres no doubt about it on paper OLED is a better picture quality, however people fall into the trap of thinking they have to get OLED.
I swapped to MiniLED after my LG OLED got burn in and i have to say these are worlds apart from your run of the mill LED TV's. For the slight difference to OLED but with no worry of burn in they are a great option, the vast majority of people would not ever notice the difference.
comment_text_original:

comment_text_display:
75" Oled for me!
I have my 55" c9 almost always on power saving (or lower brightness like 70%) as it otherwise burns my eyes in the night with ambient room lighting.
I watch a lot of TV also on the day (ends soon as I graduated lmao) and for that the "low" brightness never bothers me.
As I said for HDR movies in the night, the Oled burns my eyes when I dimm every other light in the room.
When there is a blackscreen, and the whole room is pitch black, that still gives me a massive xxx and this can't be replaced with anything other than OLED or in the future microled

comment_text_display: Good video. Gives the highlights of each technology without getting into it too deeply. I went from a 65" LG C8 (bought when the C9 came out) to an 85" Hisense UN8. I had burn-in on the C8. Too much news and business channel watching. Burn-in on the bottom and right side of the screen. I know everyone says burn-in is less likely now but obviously I am not the right candidate for OLED. I wasn't going to take the chance. I got the UN8 at 85" for about 2/3 the cost of a 77" LG C4 (last year). And don't get me started on the cost of an 85" OLED.  I am VERY happy with the UN8.

comment_text_display:
Very nice comparison. I bought a Phillips 65" 708 OLED two years ago. It's very nice but I've noticed some odd localised bright zones that aren't as bright sometimes. Like for instance in your video one side of your white shirt is very noticeably darker than the other sometimes. But then when I watch it back, the massive brightness difference is no longer there. It's really weird.

It also becomes really visible in news shows (or any show that tends to have large solid coloured graphics) where a block of colour that's supposed to be solid will have a noticeable brightness gradient.

Sorry to turn my comment into a pseudo tech support question. I really just wanted to compliment your nice video :)

comment_text_display: "Perfect motion clarity with no blur" is incorrect even on OLED TVs and their fast response time. You still get motion blur on an OLED and that is entirely down to the sample and hold scanning method all flat panels use. Only CRTs have perfect motion handling due to how briefly the phosphors are lit and that they are scanned line by line, and the entire frame isn't held until it is overwritten by the next.

comment_text_display:
@@theviewingangleThanks for the reply comment. I’m thinking about picture quality per viewing distance, mainly - straight on, primarily in a sunlit room (morning to noon).

With a smaller screen one can sit pretty close to a monitor and not detect individual pixels / LEDs. The larger the screen (which one sees better from across a room) … one might detect pixels at a viewing distance of 6 to 8 feet but not 10’ to 30’. So with your recent comparison viewing experience could one detect mini-LED pixels when sitting close to a 65 or 70+ inch mini-LED screen?

Thanks again for your post and comments reviews.

comment_text_display:
Why don't anyone take into account that movies almost NEVER uses 100% black? I have a 6 year old Samsung with local dimming and pretty bad HDR dimming. It's not the black level that makes or breaks it for me, it's the dimming of the whole screen in dark scenes. My friend just bought a lower tier QLED from Samsung and nightscenes looked FAR better but the actual black levels are about the same. All around the PQ was far better than my old tv. People are always mesmerized by demo trailers on OLED in the stores (my wife included) but the trailers are always ment to show the OLED at its best. A movie or tv-show never looks like that.

For me "the movie look" is far more important than inky blacks. It just doesn't look natural to me. Sure in animated films it looks awesome but that takes me to the other point - games! They look far better on an OLED in comparison since most games use the whole array of blacklevels. I've tested Ori on Xbox Series X on an Oled with 120hz and it looked and felt AMAZING as you say in the video about response time.

For me, nothing beats a good projector when it comes to movies!

comment_text_display:
The LG G5 you’re talking about peaks around 2400 nits. That’s VERY bright. But it pales in comparison to modern Mini-LEDs that are hitting 4000-5000 nits of brightness.

Not saying 2400 isn’t enough to clear the brightness in most rooms. Its absolutely more than enough. Even my LG G3 peaks well under 2000 nits is bright enough.

Where I think a lot of reviewers, including me, get hung up on OLED brightness vs Mini-LED is in SDR content. What most people watch. On top of that, SDR + Filmmaker mode. That’s the biggest difference in brightness between the two technologies. Granted, modern OLEDs this is practically a non-issue. But not every OLED is W-OLED or QD-OLED. So there’s still caveats needed IMO. But give it 2ish years and that talking point will go away.

comment_text_display: How far is your couch from the TV?  Surprisingly, one thing that's never talked about in these 98"/100" TV reviews is how big your living room ought to be for one.  What is too close?  Forget how far.  What's the minimum distance you need so that you don't feel blinded or uncomfortable?  Is a couch that's only 6 feet away too close?  Is 8 feet away comfortable?  Would love to see that covered in future videos, or addressed here in the comments.

comment_text_display:
I had a JVC NX7 that was replaced by a Hisense 100U76. The Hisense is better than the JVC in every way. Better white brightness, black levels, shadow detail, QD color brightness, lower input lag, 144hz with VRR, Dolby Vision, it’s cheaper, it can be used in bright sunshine, the list goes on. I’m selling the JVC because projectors are now outmoded due to the increasing size and decreasing prices of extra large direct displays. 4K projectors not only are more expensive than extra large direct displays, they still require a screen, interconnects, installation, sound system, etc. I would urge anyone looking for a big screen to also consider an extra large TV, which yields better picture quality, many of which can be acquired for well under $2000.

I will soon build a dedicated media room and it will be anchored not by a projector but with a TCL 115” mini LED.

comment_text_display: Idk if I’ll ever really consider a TV “wireless” until we get to the point where they don’t need power cords at all. Otherwise, if you’re needing to go through the trouble of hiding a dangling power cord, it’s not too hard to just run the HDMI connections along the same hidden route. I get the appeal, and how this cordless HDMI approach can be cool, but it’s certainly not a fully “wireless” TV

comment_text_display:
They should create some kind of wireless display/audio output/input protocol where game consoles & PC's can transmit video & audio wirelessly to your TV so that you don't even need any HDMI/data cables at all, nor the power chord of the wireless transmitter box.
It's ambitious & expensive, but might be better than only having the option to do wireless video/audio through a box that needs it's own power chord & video/audio cable plugged in, when the zero connect box proves that we do have the technology for a standard wireless video/audio protocol where the box itself isn't required.

Sidenote: Since the zero connect box takes up relatively little power such as compared to the TV itself, it might also be possible to at least remove the power chord from wireless video/audio transmitter boxes by plugging in a (this tech is still only being developed) no-wire power transmitter plug into an outlet in the same room, that transmitter boxes can then receive power from, but the plug would have to be small enough to easily fit on an outlet without needing it's own wire to the outlet too.

comment_text_display:
Samsung has been pioneering the One Connect Box for over a decade, consistently refining and perfecting the technology. They’ve even advanced to a truly wireless One Connect Box, delivering 40 gigabits of bandwidth superior to the LGs 30 gigabits , while also achieving lower latency. On top of that, Samsung equips it with four full HDMI 2.1 ports, plus an additional 2.1 port directly on the TV itself, giving users unmatched flexibility and future-proof performance.

Meanwhile, certain Chinese brands shamelessly copy Samsung’s innovations, right down to the name, without bringing anything genuinely original to the table. It’s a clear case of imitation rather than innovation pathetic attempts to ride on the back of Samsung’s decade of leadership and engineering excellence.

comment_text_display:
I genuinely appreciate the effort you put into your content, but I have to point out something important. Please avoid recommending products solely based on listed specifications or what’s shown on e-commerce websites. Many times, the specs provided online are either misleading or flat-out incorrect, and relying on them without proper hands-on testing can misguide your audience.
If you're reviewing a product, it needs to be based on real-world use — not just reading off a spec sheet or promotional page. Your viewers trust your opinion, and that trust can be damaged if the products don’t live up to your recommendations in actual usage.
Please take this as constructive feedback: moving forward, only recommend products you’ve personally tested and can vouch for through actual experience. Your credibility depends on it, and your audience deserves nothing less.

​​@@TheGrapevineIndiaThere are TVs and there are great TVs. Just so there are reviewers and there are great reviewers. In my assessment there are two reviewers who are good and unbiased - The Grapevine and VMOne ( Vineet Malhotra). Since both of you have the potential to be the best in the game, your followers, including me, would be unduly harsh in our comments.

Coming to the point, I agree with you but with caveats. All these features which you mentioned ( Color Gamut, HDR 10+, Refresh rate, MEMC, Sound Output, etc.,etc.) are important, no doubt. But they are important only if the TV still works after 3-4 years. And so in my opinion it is the build quality and durability of the TV that is of utmost importance and which nobody reviews.

What is build quality in a TV ?? It is the quality of components that go into it - the panel( who made it LG or TCL or some cheap manufacturer), what is the grade of the panel, who manufactured the T- Con board, what is the quality of the capacitors used ( Japanese or good Chinese like TCL or cheap generic Chinese manufacturers), etc. Furthermore, what is the pedigree of the Company. The best are of course Sony, LG and Samsung whose TVs last for 10+ years. Then, there is high quality Chinese companies who have invested in TV R&D and whose TVs last 7-8 years. And then there are marketing motor mouths like Hisense, Haier, Nokia etc. who survive only on high decibel marketing. Lastly there are the bottom feeder aggregators who buy the cheapest components, assemble it here without any sort of QC or QA.

There are details like ventilation ( heat is a big enemy) plastic or metal back panel (metal dissipitates heat fast) and so on.
An indicator of the seriousness of the companies would be the periodicity and quality of updates provided by the Company. These could be OS updates or other updates. While the high quality manufacturers like Sony are on Android 12 and 13, the cheap trash like Hisense, Haier, Xiaomi are still on Android 9 or 10. Lastly one should also review the After Sales Service which is excellent for Sony, Samsung and LG, quite good for TCL and virtually non-existent for other brands.

Sorry to be harsh. But you could be one of the best reviewer if only you stop talking about the superficial which can be gleaned from the internet and get to brass tacks.

You should try and disable HDR on whatever streaming service or games console youre using if possible. Since the TV has no Local Dimming it will probably look objectively better it you just watch in SDR and turn the backlight up.

Even with the VA panel in the 43 and 50" helping with contrast having the backlight set to max for HDR will increase the black level way beyond what it would be with SDR.

Just a suggestion to try, if you're enjoying the TV as is just continue doing that and ignore me ha.

One question for me game mode brightness is almost the same as standard mode pic is the same for you?

Its not worth the uppgrade ofcourse u will get a brighter screen with more colour but example in lg c2 the colour setting i have on that tv is on 85 same colour on lg c5 is arround 65 of 100. I regret i didnt buy lg c4/g4 instead becouse brightness is not everything its make u lose details and looks more washed out and c4/g4 have dts sound. The c5 doesnt have it.

comment_text_display:
Some points that need to be noted:
1. Of the premium segments, Mini-LEDs offer higher brightness and color volume whereas OLEDs offer better viewing angles and contrast.
2. OLEDs tend to suffer a higher rate of Burn-In in hotter areas (more than 40 degrees), so if you are planning to buy a premium TV, and you are from such an area and your living room does not have AC, go for a Mini-LED TV instead of OLED.
3. If your budget do not allow for you to get a higher tier version of latest model, go for last year model of that tier, like if Samsung QN90F (2025) is out of budget, opt for QN90D (2024). Yes QN85F (2025) has some features that looks on paper better than QN90D, but 90 series is a higher tier than 85, as such will have more local-dimming zones and better HDR management (in some cases) and so on, which results in better experience. This cannot be followed when choosing mid-range TVs, as the upgrades year-on-year is greater in those segments.
4. Hisense Q series, TCL C series are extremely good deals which offer Samsung Mini-LED QLED and Sony Mini-LED levels of performance at lower price bracket. But their other ranges are things to be debated.
comment_text_original:

1. Of the premium segments, Mini-LEDs offer higher brightness and color volume whereas OLEDs offer better viewing angles and contrast.
2. OLEDs tend to suffer a higher rate of Burn-In in hotter areas (more than 40 degrees), so if you are planning to buy a premium TV, and you are from such an area and your living room does not have AC, go for a Mini-LED TV instead of OLED.
3. If your budget do not allow for you to get a higher tier version of latest model, go for last year model of that tier, like if Samsung QN90F (2025) is out of budget, opt for QN90D (2024). Yes QN85F (2025) has some features that looks on paper better than QN90D, but 90 series is a higher tier than 85, as such will have more local-dimming zones and better HDR management (in some cases) and so on, which results in better experience. This cannot be followed when choosing mid-range TVs, as the upgrades year-on-year is greater in those segments.
4. Hisense Q series, TCL C series are extremely good deals which offer Samsung Mini-LED QLED and Sony Mini-LED levels of performance at lower price bracket. But their other ranges are things to be debated.

I genuinely appreciate the effort you put into your content, but I have to point out something important. Please avoid recommending products solely based on listed specifications or what’s shown on e-commerce websites. Many times, the specs provided online are either misleading or flat-out incorrect, and relying on them without proper hands-on testing can misguide your audience.
If you're reviewing a product, it needs to be based on real-world use — not just reading off a spec sheet or promotional page. Your viewers trust your opinion, and that trust can be damaged if the products don’t live up to your recommendations in actual usage.
Please take this as constructive feedback: moving forward, only recommend products you’ve personally tested and can vouch for through actual experience. Your credibility depends on it, and your audience deserves nothing less.

comment_text_display: Hrmm, I see you completely skipped over Dolby Vision on this set. I have the G5, and Dolby Vision content is displayed so dark that its practically unviewable in any mode except "Vivid" mode which is a mode I never ever thought I would use. SDR and HDR content is AMAZING, but Dolby Vision is hot garbage at the moment on this tv. Also the G5 seems to have memory leaks when streaming local files on the network, I've seen this happen in Emby, Plex, and the built in media player, and it seems to happen more often when viewing (you guessed it) Dolby vision content or another person on reddit found for him it was turning on subtitles . Videos would play fine for anywhere from 5-30 minutes then would start to stutter, audio would drop out for a second here and there, then the tv would black screen and give a message that the app was going to be restarted to free up memory. So far no tv updates have fixed this, I'm currently on Firmware 33.20.69 as I write this, for reference

comment_text_display: Could someone clarify something for me? When he says these TVs don’t support DTS through eARC, does that mean a sound bar that does support DTS won’t output that audio type?
comment_text_original: Could someone clarify something for me? When he says these TVs don’t support DTS through eARC, does that mean a sound bar that does support DTS won’t output that audio type?

comment_text_display: Yes, if your TV does not support DTS & you connect a soundbar via eARC, the speaker will be unable to output DTS sounds from sources connected to the TV. The TV cannot transfer an audio format that it does not recognize to your soundbar. The signal "hits a brick wall" at the television & is transformed to a more common audio format, such as stereo PCM, or there is no audio at all. So use soundbars that enable HDMI 2.1 passthrough, such as the Samsung HW-Q990F or HW-Q990D, Sony BRAVIA Theater Bar 9, and so on.
comment_text_original: Yes, if your TV does not support DTS & you connect a soundbar via eARC, the speaker will be unable to output DTS sounds from sources connected to the TV. The TV cannot transfer an audio format that it does not recognize to your soundbar. The signal "hits a brick wall" at the television & is transformed to a more common audio format, such as stereo PCM, or there is no audio at all. So use soundbars that enable HDMI 2.1 passthrough, such as the Samsung HW-Q990F or HW-Q990D, Sony BRAVIA Theater Bar 9, and so on.
